For decades companies have designed and manufactured so many different kinds of air fresheners and odor eliminators to freshen the air inside the drivers compartment of the automobile; beginning I suppose with the scented green cardboard pine tree that was designed to dangle conspicuously from the rearview mirror. Not to be outdone, Febreze offers a new air freshener that clips to a vehicle's air vent.

The liquid Febreze is encased in a compact silver and gray plastic container (measuring about 1" x 1" x ") with a straight plastic close-pin type clip on the back, allowing the air freshener to be pushed tightly on to a vent louver. Located on the top edge of this air freshener is a slider that governs the fragrance strength. This is an important feature because the fragrance in this product is strong, so I recommend starting at the lowest setting first or your nose just may go into sensory shock. There are around a half dozen different scents available.

This air freshener is designed to be used with the aid of the vehicle's air vent. In my opinion, this product works great without a vent. In fact, I found using it with a vent too overwhelming, even at the lowest setting. I ended up putting mine at the lowest setting and placing it in one of the passenger cup holders just behind the center console in my sedan. Perfect! The smell is subtle rather than eye watering, and my air freshener has lasted over twice as long as advertised, too. According to Febreze, this air freshener will last 30 days.

I selected a Febreze air freshener with the "Meadows and Rain" scent. Though I can't say the fragrance reminds me of a meadow during or after a rain, I still like the fresh clean scent.

Postscript (14 Jan 2014): I don't know what I am doing right but the air freshener is still producing a subtle scent; a little less than earlier but still a nice fragrance. This Febreze product has definitely performed better than expected. Just keep it at the lowest setting.
summary: Febreze Car Vent Clips Air Freshener and Odor Eliminator

This device does what it is advertised to do as long as the battery is sulfated and none of the cells have gone bad.  What I mean by this is that discharging a battery and leaving it discharged causes sulfation, but leaving it too low for too long causes irreversible damage.  This device serves to correct sulfation, and I have found this to be true in my experience.

First, I use a 1 amp trickle changer and a battery tester that checks voltage and CCA by type of battery.  It does not test under load, but gives a general idea if the battery is bad or not.

I started off with 2 batteries, one a motorcycle SL 260 CCA and, and the other an AMG 760 CCA.

The motorcycle battery sat at about 8v or less for almost a month. I equalized it, checked the fluid level, and put a trickle charger and desulfator on it.  I was able to bring it back up to hold 11 v for 24hrs and would get about 230 CCA.  After a few days it would be dead again.  Pretty clear indication one of the cells had reversed polarity and the battery is no good, no amount of desulfation can correct this.

The 760 AH battery on the other hand, had died a couple times and was having a hard time getting and holding a full charge.  It would fall to about 12.4v over the course of a week, and I would get a reading of about 700 CCA.  After about a month and a half on a trickle change with the desulfator, the battery holds at 12.8v and I am getting 770 CCA.

If you have the patience (and the battery you are trying to restore is not destroyed) this thing is great.  I ordered more for other batteries and friends.  Customer service is top notch, I found one came faulty in the mail.  I reached out to the manufacturer and they sent a brand new one and apologized for the inconvenience.

Note: I have found that hooking this up in parallel with any device that relies on voltage for readings with really screw with things.  I would personally not leave it hooked up on our high end imports that rely on complex and sensitive computer systems.  I would leave it hooked up on my toyota without too much concern.

UPDATE: (one year later)
I purchased the TireTech TP7001 Wireless Tire Pressure Monitoring System on Amazon a year ago. Last summer I had a blowout on the front axle and I believe that tire knocked the one off behind it, so two tires. At the time I came to the conclusion that I forgot to turn on the TMS and let it sync before we left the camp area. Because it went into alarm about 15 minutes AFTER the blowout when I hit the ON button to see why it didn't alarm.
Working with company now to see if we can resolve the issue.

I purchased two new tire monitors last month to replace the ones I lost before a long tip last weekend.

This week on the way home I had another blowout and NO alarms on the TMS. (My complaint with the tires is another topic) I specifically took the time at camp to turn on the TMS and ensure all the tire monitors where in sync and the system was working as intended. I even scrolled through the tires as we traveled and watched the pressures and temps slowly increase. As I was changing the flat my wife walks up to tell me the TMS just went into alarm. I had already taken the tire monitor off and put it in the truck.

I spent $200 for the system and $80 for two replacement tire monitors for a product failed to work as advertised, twice.

I saw all the rave reviews and the photo made these towels look exceptionally plush, just what I had been looking for.  I saw one review that reported surprise at all the rave reviews and found the towels disappointing.  I guess it depends on how particular you are but I agree with the latter reviewer.  These towels are better than the bulk Walmart type (they should be for the cost!) but they are not the luxurious high end towel you might be expecting.  The "silk" binding is really cheap looking and the stitching looks like the mass produced product that this is.  They are not as plush as the photo suggests.  If you are just looking for a thicker towel that is better than most you'll be happy with them.  However, I am extremely particular about my detailing supplies and if that describes you then pass on these towels and find something else.  I have a large towel from Griot (with pockets) that is a bit of a pain to use but the quality is absolutely there (the towel cost about $25).  I find that the reviewers at Amazon often provide great info and I'll be looking at other reviews to find leads on the high end towels I'm looking for.  I've ordered some standard sized towels from Griot and will report on those after the arrive.  Hope this helps.

Update July 9 2013.  I received Griot towels the other day (blue, about the same price as these) and they are MUCH better.  There is some lint but it shakes off easily and prewashing is not required.  The Griot towels are what you are looking for if you want the Porsche of detailing towels.

I searched a lot before deciding to buy this product as I was looking for a kit that would work for servicing my 2 bikes (a Suzuki vstrom DL650 and a Honda Valkyrie I/S).

I received the kit on the promised date and read the instructions carefully as also watched videos on youtube teaching how to use the product. Even went through the trouble of sealing the break line bleed valve with teflon tape when installing the kit drain tubing.

When I got started bleeding the breaks from my Vstrom, it started leaking air through the drain oil reservoir and not only was unable to keep a vacuum but instead *injected* air through the motorcycle brake lines (to the point of making air bubbles to boil the oil on the motorcycle brake reservoir, spilling oil over the place).

The damage wasn't even bigger because I was careful and protected all the area around the gas tank with paper towels before getting started (but otherwise, it would have ruined the gas tank paint as DOT4 fluid damages painted surfaces).

I had to drain the brake lines 4 times using the goodie and oldie method of pumping the brake lever to get ridden of all the air that mityvac introduced into my motorcycle's brakes. Wasted 3x the time to perform a simple operation and could have damaged my motorcycle.

To add insult to the injury, to return this I had to visit a UPS store and buy a cardboard box (7USD = box + assembly) as the UPS pick up guy refused to receive the kit in its case with no cardboard box. Factor in the cost of gas to drive from my place to the nearby UPS store and you see that this was not only a waste of time but made me loose money. I bought this to save time and not having to ask help while doing a simple maintenance operation.

Searching about the issue, it seem that is quite common for the drain oil reservoir to leak air (and the 'fix' of adding teflon tape around its cover didn't work too).

Final remark: if you are lucky and got one that is not leaking, you may be happy. But I have the impression that this is like flipping a coin (and I definitely don't like to rely on luck when comes to tools).
summary: Great kit: if at least it was able to keep a vacuum!

Perfect fit for my 2008 Mazda 3 hatchback, with 2.3 liter engine!  This is super-easy to install, and will save you hundreds over going to the dealership and having them do it for you.  What you'll needs is two wheel ramps, a floor jack, ratchet wrench, torque wrench, extension extender (used between the socket and the ratchet wrench), and a 17 millimeter deep socket.  Replacing the engine mount should take 30 - 45 minutes.

The first thing you'll need to do is drive your car up on the wheel ramps, and then remove the plastic engine cover on the bottom of the car.  Once this is done, place a piece of wood or rubber jack pad on the saddle of the floor jack, and then lift the engine slightly by placing the saddle of the floor jack beneath the oil pan of the engine.  The engine doesn't need to be lifted much, and this will not damage the oil pan.

Once the engine has been lifted, with the hood raised, remove the clear plastic coolant reservoir, that is over the engine mount.  This reservoir is held in place by two metal clips.  A flat head screwdriver may be needed to help.  After this is done, the only thing left is to remove the two bolts that hold the engine mount to the car, and then the two nuts that hold the engine to the mount; the 17 millimeter socket will be needed for this, and specifically a deep socket will be needed to remove the two nuts.  Before you begin, you may want to place a cloth over the passenger-side fender to make sure you don't chip any paint.

The engine may shift as you start loosening the nuts and bolts, however the floor jack should hold it in place.  After you've removed the two bolts and nuts, the mount should come out easily, and the new one put in its place.  The engine may need to be lifted some more with the floor jack so that bolts from the engine stick far enough through the mounts to put the nuts on.  Be sure and confirm what the torque settings are for the nuts and bolts; there's plenty of online videos with this information on them to watch.  The coolant reservoir is easy to put back in it's place as well as the plastic engine cover on the bottom of the are.

This is a very simple process, and anybody who is able to change their own oil can do it, and it'll save you hundreds over having the dealership do it for you.  Good luck!

Cannot praise these bulbs enough.  They are bright as can be, a perfect match for my HIDs, color temperature is a great match.  I have the same bulbs (but with a different socket) on my truck, and they match the LED headlights I put in that vehicle.  Attached is a picture of my MX-5 with LED driving lights (center, top, next to the grille,) HID low beams (top, outside,) and the driver's side (bottom right in picture) is this bulb, and opposite it is the original halogen.

It is difficult to tell in the picture unless you look carefully, but these LEDs are much brighter and produce a much cleaner (cooler) light than the halogens they replaced.  Speaking of "cool" - they do not generate much heat at all.  I touched the glass lens on the fog lights, and the LED was cool to the touch, the glass lens in front of the halogen was hot enough to cook an egg.

Unfortunately, for the purposes of picture-taking, it was not possible to turn the fog lamps on without the headlights turned on without completely unplugging everything else, so again, you have to look closely at the picture to tell the difference.  As I stated in other reviews of the same bulbs with different sockets for other vehicles, they simply must be seen to be believed.

Everyone I've shown these bulbs to has been completely blown away, and I've helped several friends to bring their vehicles up-to-date on lighting - find your exact socket and order these lights that fit - these 144 SMD LEDs are unbeatable.

Got this for my Toyota FJ Cruiser 4x4 TRD.
I had BF Goodrich mud terrain t/a 265 75 16 which is $250 each. Going mud terrain to all terrain was like night and day. My BF Goodrich did great job on off road but it just performed miserably on the road(where 99% of my drivings are).
Installed at local Sams Club(lifetime rotation/balance) and drove 900 mile roadtrip for Christmas vacation.
I'm loving this tire.
Hankook is significantly quieter, softer, cheaper, and kept same aggressive look on my truck.

I did extensive research before getting this tire.
I was deciding between General Grabber AT2(265/70/16), Nitto Grappler(265/70/16), and Hankook Dynapro(265/75/16).
Those three were the top choices I made while searching for all terrain with aggressive look.
Hankook was cheapest($20 cheaper per tire), had good/most reviews, and also kept stock OEM size. Other two tires also had good reviews but there were not that many reviews out there.
Hankook advertise their Dynapro ATM has wider 6-7% footprint and I believe it. It looks bigger and wider than my previous tire.

So do I miss my BF Goodrich? Hell no.
I paid only half the cost of BF Goodrich with same aggressive look and softer/quieter ride.
I don't think I'll even try other two I had on the list when this tire wears out in couple years.

I'll also recommend this tire to my dad's Tundra.
summary: Came from BF Goodrich to DynaPro with zero regret.

My wife's daily driver is a 2011 VW Jetta TDi.  If you've been in the latest version of the Jetta lately, or any compact/sub-compact, you know there's a lot of road noise coming into the cabin.

Note: We had this product installed concurrently with four 10435 Door kits.

After 18 months, I finally convinced my wife to let us try this out under the condition it was professionally installed.  No problem, saves me the headache of dealing with it myself.  I wish I could tell you a bit more about the installation.  However, I will reiterate what everyone else says, make sure your application surface is clean of oils and debris.

Before the dynamat was installed, you heard every bump as well as felt it.  You heard the noise of the tires from the road through the doors.  If you are soft spoken, conversation was difficult on the freeway.  To put it simply; It was loud.

We had all four doors plus the trunk covered in dynamat.  The difference was huge.  Bumps are now only felt, and not heard.  The stereo system sounds a bit better, not to mention you don't have to turn it up to accommodate speed increase.  The doors close with a more solid thunk.  And best of all, no more road noise!!! Hooray!  My wife called me up this morning and said even she noticed a big difference!!

As a post-script to this review.  We've ordered the bulk pack kit 10455 to have the floors covered.  Now my wife notices the noise coming from the floors.  I told her, "The noise was always there, you just never heard it because of the doors".
summary: A must for any noisy car, after you start with the doors.

reviewText:
I also got one for review, and I love it.

I've suffered through a couple of stands, and their downfall usually is that they aren't beefy enough. I paid a lot for a tablet, and I don't want it falling.

The TaoTronics stand has some very nice features in this regard. First, it's got a ratcheting hinge with a release. Not a friction hinge, but one with catches so that it's less likely to creep open if you put pressure on the tablet. And it has a release, so that it won't open up unless you take positive action to do so.

Second, it's beefy enough. The rear leg isn't too narrow, or too wide. It resists torsion And third, it's got some non slip rubber with a bit of lip so that the tablet doesn't go flying. Which is bad.

The bottom has a recessed area that can allow for an Apple lightning connector to be attached to the bottom and still fit in the stand, without too much strain on the cord. Unfortunately, that isn't so much the case with a Samsung Galaxy Tab Pro; the OEM USB end is a bit bigger than Apple's connector, and it hits. So you have to flip the tablet 180 degrees. Not a huge thing, but it might mean this is less suitable for that tablet. On the plus side, even with an Otterbox enclosure on my Tab it fit in the stand securely. The gap is about 13mm wide, so use that to judge if your case can fit (it's a bit wider in effect since the back lip isn't critical).

2005 F-250 Super Duty with 6.0L Powerstroke diesel.  In this engine, the engine oil is highly compressed and used to actuate the fuel injectors.  This abuses the oil something fierce.  Always use synthetic oil in the 6.0L.  Worse with petroleum but also happens with the synthetic more slowly, a common issue called "stiction" occurs when the oil leaves a plaque in the injector spool valves, which causes rough running and smoke in cool weather, problem goes away when engine is warm.  Can appear to be a transmission problem because the shifting occurs late and harshly.  Replacing injectors would be the ultimate fix but these chemicals solve the problem if you keep using them with each oil change during cold months.  I'm now a couple hundred miles into the first dose, and it works as well as Rev-X.  Half the price, makes it a winner!

Good match for my 2006 Silverado 2500HD's original fob - but more colorful!. I got blue so I can instantly distinguish my truck key ring from others laying around. The button action is a little different than the original - you have to push with a bit more force 'til you feel a soft click. Other than that, it opens and locks the doors just like a GM fob, but at a fraction of the price. As others have noted, programming is easy. My only complaint has to do with the battery. The fob stopped working after about a year. Seemed a short lifespan for a fob battery, esp. for a rig that's not driven too often, but I replaced the battery and that got the fob working again. It went dead again with weeks, so I replaced the battery again, and again it died within weeks. Changing the battery again with one fresh-off-the shelf, I noticed that a tiny LED on the circuit board lit up intermittently as I was sliding the new battery into its holder, sort of a metal cage with one open side and little tabs on top that double as conductors and retainers. I'd also noticed that the old battery was protruding slightly from the open side of the holder before I removed it. I think the battery goes dead so quickly because it gradually nudges out of its cage to where it makes contact with a nearby bit of metal on the circuit board. That lights up the LED, but there must be some other power draw, too. The good news is it doesn't actuate my truck's locks. My fix - I hope, it's only a week old so far - was to use the protective sticker off the new battery to insulate the metal on the circuit board and hold the battery more securely in its cage. Hopefully, the manufacturer will discover and fix this design flaw at some point, because it's otherwise a great deal.
summary: Works like original, but battery holder needs improvement

I would have given 5 stars if had more confidence to use the replacement studs that came with the hubs.  Other posts had indicated they are junk even though the hubs are excellent.  OEM studs are grade 8.8 metric (~= to grade 5 SAE).  The replacement studs included with the hubs have no grade marking on them so they could very well be junk and unsuitable for use.  It was not worth the risk using them so I threw them away and used the OEM studs.
On a positive note: Switching out the OEM drive flanges with these hubs has reduced the a large amount drag on my engine performance when I have the hubs unlocked, running free. The CV joints will also see reduced wear because they no longer rotate when the hubs are running free.  I expect there will be some MPG improvement as well, driving in 4 X 2, since the wheels are no longer burdened with turning the front end differential and drive axles.  Why Nissan failed to equip automatic locking free running hubs into all their 4 X 4s that are not all wheel drive is just cheap and dumb.  At least I found a manual locking free running hub that fits perfectly and will likely pay for itself in reduced wear and tear and fuel efficiency.  The auto parts apps that tell you what parts fit with your car will indicate this hub will not fit a 2002 Nissan Pathfinder because the stock hub caps are in the way.  With a bit of skill and dremel the center of the hub cap can be cut out so that it will fit.  The Nissan logo on the hub cap just happens to be the perfect size and style to be applied to the locking hub, using heavy duty mounting tape so that you get a factory stock look.

I was provided a sample of the Miucolor trunk organizer for evaluation, and having had experience with other similar organizers, it was very noticeable that this item was heavier than normal.

Like most organizers of this type, the outer covering is made of durable nylon material.  The backing material sewn inside the nylon appears to be cardboard panels, which is typical, but for some reason they seem to be heavier and perhaps denser, which may translate to a structure that may be sturdier.

If the organizer will just sit in your trunk, a little more reinforcement may not make much difference, unless you do a lot of rough driving.  But if the organizer is in situation where it slides around and is subject to impact, like in the bed of a truck, toughness may become a factor.

Held together by Velcro type fasteners, putting the parts together takes just a few minutes.  The organizer measures about 21 by 14, and is 12 high.  There are provisions to divide the main compartment into up to three separate sections.  Installing both dividers is not necessary, but having at least one in place keeps the structure stable.

There are a total of four large net pockets and two covered pockets on the exterior sides, for holding smaller items.  On the bottom of the organizer are Velcro fasteners to help keep the assembly from sliding on a carpeted surface.  Also included is a lid that covers the entire top of the organizer, and a decent sized insulated carry bag as a bonus.

This heavy duty organizer is one of the larger and tougher ones that I have seen so far.  This model does not appear to be a generic product that is being sold by several sellers.  If you need a larger organizer which is durable, take a look at this one.  The cost is higher, so unless you really need the space or durability, you could probably get by with a less expensive option.
summary: a very heavy duty trunk organizer

I have been using paint clay on my car for a number of years, but only recently bought glass clay for the first time. It worked very well. I am attaching a collage of 5 photos and will be referencing the photos by the unique numbers that each photo was labelled with. 1) The stock photo is somewhat deceiving as it makes you think the clay fills the nice container it is shipped in. Photo #1 shows the clay in the plastic wrap is it arrived, and photo #2 a clay ball after I worked with it. The amount of clay is sufficient to work with, I am not complaining about that, just the photo makes you think you get a lot more. The container itself is very nice for storage. The paint clay I used before is Mother's clay - love the product - but I had to come up with a plastic container of my own. A tip on storage: before storing the clay ball in the container wet the outside of the clay ball with Griot's Speed Shine or any other detailing spray. This makes the clay easier to take out the next time as it sticks less to the container. 2) Photos #4 and #5 show the windshield glass before and after. As you can see the difference is significant, and it was fairly easy to get it that clean. All glass surfaces took no more than 20 minutes and that included taking photos for this review. The clay removed water stains as well as some non-bird droppings (I think dragonfly or some other insect) which are hard to remove with just soap and water. 3) Photo #3 shows the trick that allows me to reach the glass that it too far away for me to reach by hand. I am fairly short so reaching the middle of the sunroof and the middle of my windshield is not possible for me without a stepping stool. I found that it was a lot easier to to put the clay ball under a triangle-shaped Glass Reach and Clean Tool and use it to rub the clay ball on the glass that I could not reach. The clay worked well to remove debris, but it was fairly sticky and my hands were slightly blue when I finished. I was able to remove the residue from my hands using Griot's Speed Shine followed by a vigorous washing with soap. Thumbs up overall! Ali Julia review
summary: Works well, before and after photos attached

I have read many reviews regarding the problem of getting the bike off this type of stand.  I have this exact stand and have been using this carrier for around 4 years and at first I encounter the same problem.  Getting the bike off the carrier is a high reach for most average size adults unless you are 6' 6" tall and strong like bull.

My technique is not to pull the bike back and off the ramp but to put the ramp at the front side of the carrier and start the engine, put it in first and slowly power the bike down forward using the clutch.

I do have the lean the bike on the back of the truck first then push the front tire back an inch to slip the ramp in but its so easy once you do it twice.  Trust me and good luck, you will enjoy the carrier 1000 times more.
One more thing, you do have to pay attention to leave enough room when you park your truck.

I also added trailer lights to the back to increase the safety factor.

Very happy with it.  No more trailer for hauling a single bike, less toll and less gas used.
summary: Solution to problem of getting the bike off the carrier.

These are amazingly bright, compact lights, and mounting could not be easier.  On fishing boats, bumpers, bars and more.  I actually use a pair in the back yard on a motion detector and 12V landscaping power supply. If someone walks around the yard, they get blinded by these puppies.

The part on the bottom of the light where the mounting hardware is attached can be moved left or right, then locked in place with two Allen screws (wrench included.)  This gives you more mounting options and is a pretty handy feature.  All the hardware (except the Allen screws) is Stainless steel, the housings Aluminum, and the lens and reflector, plastic.

I measured the draw, and each light pulls 1 amp. If the lights are dim, you have a wiring or power problem. If you're replacing current lights, this should not be a problem. If you're adding to them, check your available amps.

The lights throw a nice spot, with about 20% spill into a wide beam, and are great anywhere you have a 12V power source. For the price, you can find a lot of uses. For example, using as a spot to illuminate a flag, portable battery powered spotlight, etc.

Free sample provided for honest review.
summary: Very versatile and well made lights, easy to install and extremely bright.

reviewText:
I have a shelf full of waxes, polymers and hybrids. Yes the others are great but this has been my "Go To" dressing. Let me tell you why.

It is fast, simple and provides lubricity when applying. It leaves major water beading so when I drive off to work in the morning the morning dew hovers an it seems that all the water (and dirt) rolls right off the car. Maybe this is why my car seems to stay cleaner longer.

But it is so easy to use, I wipe on, wipe off. No waiting no hazing nonsense also I no longer need to be careful about going near edges or moldings because there is no wax residue. I used it on glass, headlights, taillights windows and side mirrors.  You can wipe this stuff over anything with no issues.
It smells like a Pez candy so enjoyable to use. It is inexpensive and wipes down easy.
It seems to last longer than most of my other spray ons.  I highly recommend this stuff if you want something quick and easy.
summary: Wipe on Wipe off massive beading, too easy!

This was our second front bumper installation in the past year.  Our first was a Smittybilt SRC bumper on a 2009 Wrangler X, which though stated "easy" installation, required drilling through the steel frame and was anything but "easy."  This Rugged Ridge XHD bumper truly was a simple bolt on process using existing holes in the frame.  The factory OEM fog lamps fit easily into the provided openings and attach securely using nuts.  After removing the 2012 Wrangler Sport's factory bumper, the actual installation of the Rugged Ridge bumper took two people 30 minutes.  NO drilling.  NO alteration.  Straight forward nut and bolt installation.

Our only complaint about the bumper might be the quality.  The bumper has two end caps with 3 bolts per end holding them on.  It arrived with one bolt snapped off and laying in the box.  While I am sure two bolts are sufficient, one has to question that someone packaged the bumper with the snapped off bolt laying there.

We will probably be ordering the Rugged Ridge 11540.12 Textured Black XHD Front Bumper Ends, but that is purely an aesthetic decision.  There is lots of clearance with the short base bumper which won't be inhibited by the ends.

Nice system that allows you to customize your bumper to fit your needs or looks!

I was disappointed with mine after unboxing and installing it this weekend. It works, but it usually constantly bumps the winch as if you're tapping the button, when you are in fact holding the button down. You can hear the contactor smashing off and on repeatedly. This will surely kill the contactor if I continue to use it. The only way it works smoothly is if I open the hood and point the remote straight at the receiver, holding the remote up high in the air. I emailed warn about it and all they said was move the receiver to an open location. But with the hood open, it is in an open location, and it still barely works from 20 feet away. Also moving the receiver would mean that I would have to move my winch contactor, because the receiver plugs into the contactor box. I can't do that, because I spent hundreds of dollars on 1/0 cable and spent hours relocating the contactor up high in the engine bay to keep it out of water. I had to weld some mounts for it into the side of the fender under the hood. It would take me hours and more wiring to relocate it again, that ain't happenin. It wouldn't matter anyway since it still doesn't work with the hood open unless I hold the remote up high in the air and pointed directly at it. When you're trying to direct a complicated and dynamic recovery with multiple snatch blocks you can not concentrate on standing there pointing the remote in the exact right spot to get it to work! I will be running a hard mounted switch into the cab and only use this wireless remote if I absolutely have to be out of the truck.
summary: I was disappointed with mine after unboxing and installing it this weekend

I believe this is a remanufactured oem denso honda alternator. It is exactly like the original alternator I took off the car with the exception of a denso sticker in place of the honda sticker (with denso written on it as well). I also believe it's the identical unit from the oem manufacturer because the unit I got was from amazon warehouse for forty two dollars and I was able to use a part off the old alternator on this one. The condition was described as "used-like new." When I received the alternator, it was indeed in new condition, but the positive terminal that connects the alternator to the battery was bent, and the plastic housing around the terminal was shattered. I suppose someone dropped it on the terminal at some point. Anyhow, I was able to take the cover off the original alternator and screw it onto this one, thus allowing me to connect the rubber boot over the positive terminal. Unit works perfectly, although I only have about 100 miles on it so far. It's exceedingly well built. So well, in fact, that after examining it, I felt safe putting it in my car despite suspecting someone dropped it. My original oem alternator for my 2003 accord 4 cylinder, which is also a denso, was still working, but I'm a preventive maintenance guy. There was no core charge so I still  have the old alternator as a spare. Will probably put new brushes in it. My 2003 accord coupe 4 cylinder manual has 110,000 miles on it. Next up is the water pump! This is a great product, and I got a steal from amazon warehouse. Very satisfied. Even if you pay regular price, this is the best option. The denso alternators appear to last forever. Atleast that's what the people in the honda forums say.

I wanted to add some comments regarding installation. It is fairly easy for the accord coupe 4 cylinder that I have. The tools you need are a serpentine belt bar tool, a 14mm socket, a 12mm socket (with extension or deep socket) 10mm wrench or socket, and a socket wrench (I used a flex head which made reaching bottom bolts easier). Obviously you disconnect the battery. Use a 14mm socket and serpentine belt tool on the tensioner to remove the serpentine belt (push towards the front of the car on the serpentine belt tool). Then on to the alternator. Once you get the 3 retaining bolts unscrewed with a 12mm socket, you need to disconnect the wiring harness and the positive terminal with a 10mm wrench or socket. It's actually easier to disconnect the bolts, then hold the alternator and use a 10mm socket (especially true when reinstalling) on the positive terminal. To get the alternator out, you should pull up on your power steering fluid reservoir and move it back towards the engine a bit, and do the same for the electrical fitting attached to the radiator. Just detach from the radiator to give you more room for extraction. Slide the detached alternator under the A/C line (you will need to push the line towards the engine) and it just comes on out of there. When reinstalling, attach the top bolt first but leave it loose, then you can move the alternator to give you enough room to use a socket wrench on the positive terminal (it's a tight fit if you install alternator and then attempt to secure the bolt). Then bolt on the bottom two retaining bolts using your 12mm socket. Torque the 12mm retaining bolts in to 192 in/lbs or 16 ft/lbs with a torque wrench. Reattach the serpentine belt and you're good.
summary: Fantastic alternator from Honda OEM manufacturer for alternators

reviewText:
OVERVIEW
I have never had a cracked light but I seen these on another jeep and I wanted them! These will give the blackout look with added protection. It gives the vehicle a rugged appearance. I have all gloss black on black so I chose the gloss black even though they have other options. I purchased LED taillight upgrades you'll see in the photo that have a reflecter sticking out on the side slightly farther than the stock rear light housings. I would worried this wouldn't fit but they have enough space and even wrap around for a larger caged look.

 INSTALLATION
 It only took me about five minutes to install these alone.  With another person helping you this may take only a minute. The hardest part was just balancing it to get the first screw going. It fits right in line with the stock location and housing. No extra drill holes or anything crazy like that are needed.  Screws are provided with a little extra length to make up for the added width of the guard. I like how the don't directly touch the light and there is some room to absorb a hit in case something hits the guard (it shouldn't transfer the blast to the light cracking it). Enjoy the photos as I am pleased. They are as steady as the housing was without the guard in place so the extended screws didn't jeopardize the light housing installation integrity. The product is heavy and not cheap tin foil. I appreciate the curved bar engineering that looks like it can absorb a blast similar to metal bars underneath an airline seat for crash landings.

PRICE
$-$$ out of $$$$$ based on the seller I went with. I receive Jeep enthusiest magazines with custom products for sale and these same guards cost two to four times what is listed here.  However, seeing them in person, they are worth the price and I'll be looking for matching sets for the rest of my jeep's lights.
summary: Put the monkeys in a cage for their own protection and a rugged look

1st off I wish I bought my Tiger Shark 9500 from Amazon. I would have saved $50.00. With that said, I have had my Superwinch Tiger Shark 9500 for exactly 1 year as of this review. I have used it to rescue myself 5 times and to help others about the same. The most I have used it was on Pritchett Canyon in Moab Utah. I used it on Axle Hill, Rock Pile, and Chewy. I used it at Cleveland Rock on the Holy Cross Trail in Colorado to name just a few places.  A little note on reliability. We had 4 rigs on Pritchett Canyon with 4 different brand of winches. Our trail leader had a Warm winch but I am not sure of the model, my Uncle has a Ramsey REP8000, my brother has a Smittybilt XRC-9.5, and of course my Superwinch Tiger Shark 9500. By the end of the day only tje Warn and my Superwinch had not malfunctioned or quit. The Smittybilt stopped free spooling requiring it to be powered out. The Ramsey was having control box or remote issues and intermittently worked.
So what are the pro's and con's?

Pro's: All stainless hardware, water proof construction, heavy-duty drive train, Superwinch quality control, safety circuit breakers included, waterproof remote, easy to use clutch, lowest amp draw un it's class, Price!!!.

Con's: Made in China, slow no load line speed, 10 pounds heavier then a Warn M8000, no lifetime warranty.

In my judgement, I believe the pro's outweighed the con's. Time will tell if it will be as reliable as the Warn M8000 by which all winches are compared.
For the price and quality I can't say anything negative

I bought this 24" antenna for an '02 Ford F250 Super Duty that had a 32" antenna so that the truck will fit in the garage.  The problem with this antenna kit are the adapters, specifically the small adapter required for the factory Ford antenna base.  If the adapters were made out of a decent qualit and properly heat treated steel or stainless steel it wouldn't be a problem but you can see in the photo that the adapter sheared off and that was without much torque at all.  I put some blue Loctite on the threads of the adapter and applied minimal torque but adapter sheared off.  The diameter of the shank is about .100" and with such poor steel it simply can't stand up to the necessary torque to properly secure the antenna.  To fix this issue I used an appropriately sized drill bit to drill out the factory antenna base and then cut threads in the base with a 1/4-20 tap. I then used the 1/4-20 adapter in the kit to attach the new antenna.  It was very easy to drill out the sheared off stub that was stuck in the factory base which tells me that the steel is very soft.  Once I got the antenna mounted I'm pleased with the results.  Radio reception is good, the antenna looks factory, and the truck fits in the garage.  I took two stars off this product due to the poor quality of the adapters.
summary: Antenna is fine but the adapters are of poor quality, particularly the smaller diameter ones.

reviewText:
Well - to start, I always give reviews, normally in detail, on every thing I get from Amazon. You can see this by searching my reviews. This product was given to me in trade for a HONEST review, and that is what you will get.

I am a profesional controls Steamfitter, which I have to rely on my meters to be perfect. So this review will be based on over 30 years of experience in the trades.

I agree with the other reviews given, a small case to hold the pieces would be nice, but would add cost, I have many cases for holding these so it is not a big deal to me. The leads them self are more for a amateur or home owner for tinkering around. Running the leads through several test and comparing them to Fluke leads as I use mostly Fluke meters.

Resistance using my Fluke 789 ($1000 meter) and a Fluke 87 ($400 meter) Fluke probes = 0.0 ohms, while these leads were 0.2 ohms. This is normal on lighter gauge wires. It also only matters for taking professional reading, home owners would not see an issue.

Wire gauge - Using a digit caliper, I tested the wire is several locations and come up with 2.54 mm(.100"). The claims were 2.8 mm. The Fluke leads in comparison are 3.58 mm (.141").  The ends are threaded which makes it fairly easy to take and switch ends to/from probes or alligator clips. This makes it nice if you wish to get a quick jumper wire. Quality of the insulation is very good, and passed a 600 volt meg ohm meter test, but I would not grade them as Class 3. (see photos)

Lead ends - The cute alligator clips cover up the threaded ends making it hard to put on the leads. The probe end is 2.0 mm as stated but the length is 22.5 mm and not the 18 mm as stated. Again, this is not a big deal, just being exact.

Meter lead end - This was a disappointment as they were loose in my older Fluke 87, but OK in the Fluke 789. They also leave exposed metal even when seated all the way in. This could lead to a dangerous condition when reading high voltage. ( see photos )

So - are these "the best multimeter test leads"? Compared to the ones that come with a $30 meter, they are better. Compare to what we use on higher end instruments, not even close. With that said.... Do you need to spend $60 on test leads for you home projects? No, not at all. These will work fine and the wire quality is more important making them a good value for the money.

Now the reason for 4 stars - Exposed metal at meter on leads, alligator screw ends should have been longer - insulations not covering screws. It was thinking closer to 3 stars, but these are again for amateurs, not professionals.

I purchased this over a year ago, placed it in a corner of the garage and forgot about it.  Or at least I kept putting off installing it.  After my last wheeling excursion over some boulders and stuff I decided I needed to take care of business so it went on this week.

The instructions are minimal with poor photos.  Anyone experienced with jeeps and mechanics won't have a problem but I can see where someone without experience and a good tool set could have issues installing it.  Better instructions for novices would be an improvement.  It seems to me that many of the companies making aftermarket Jeep parts have great products but don't know how to write up decent procedures.

Having an extensive tool set and plenty of wrenching experience, it was just a matter of removing a bunch of nuts and bolts (along with the transfer case skid plate, front cross bar and cross member), installing the two mounting brackets and the plate, and then reassembling everything.  The clearance between the transmission pan and the exhaust is really tight.  I used a persuader (3 lb. mallet).  Oh, and you need to support the transfer case with a jack before removing the cross member.  Failing to do this could result in flattened body parts.

All in all the skid is high quality, looks good and should protect the trans pan and cooling line.  Better instructions and I'd have given it 5 stars.

There are a lot of reviews that talk about fogging, talk about the size being too tight, or talk about a litany of other problems. I can tell you that from my experience, and the experiences of three of my friends, we experienced NONE of these problems. This is a quality helmet at a price that won't break your wallet. Below is my experience.

I'm learning to ride a motorcycle and this is my first motorcycle helmet and, not going to lie, I felt overwhelmed by the number of choices. I chose this helmet because a friend of mine, who is a gear head and whom I trust, purchased this helmet for himself. I measured my head and, despite the reviews complaining of sizing issues, purchased the helmet that matched the HJC sizing guide. It arrived on time, and I couldn't wait to put it on. It was very tight that first time, so tight I even wondered that first day whether I had gotten too small a size, but at my wife's advising, I decided to give it a couple more days to break in. I wore it a few times while watching Netflix to get used to the feel and finally got to take it for it's maiden ride as a passenger on the back of another friend's motorcycle. During this ride, he wore my other friends HJC helmet just to compare to his cheap Walmart helmet. "A helmet is a helmet" he said. "Why should I pay more?" At the end of this ride, I had no more doubts. There was almost no wind noise and the ventilation was very cooling. I could actually feel the air hitting my head through the vents. The fogging, which I thought might be a problem, was not an issue at all out on the road, and at times, the helmet was so comfortable, I hardly noticed I was even wearing it. Another interesting thing, though, happened at the end of this ride. My friend I had rode with, who had the cheap Walmart helmet, promptly went into the house, logged in to Amazon, and purchased an HJC helmet for himself. As it stands, in my group of six close friends, four of us now own this exact model HJC helmet, and my wife has requested that I purchase this helmet for her when I'm ready to put her on the back of my bike.

My advice, buy this helmet with confidence.
summary: My advice, buy this helmet with confidence.

reviewText:
Many say it will not work - simply follow the instructions and it works fine !!!
I will tell you a little secret - USE your old bolts!....and take the new gasket, line it up to your tank, make a mark on it corresponding to a mark on the tank (like a permanent marker) - then place the sender on the tank WITHOUT the gasket - line it up and mark the sender to the mark on the tank. Sounds a bit long winded - but it is hard to look through the metal flange and the gasket to get it lined up.

Place all five bolts through the metal and the gasket before placing it back on the tank, start each one - they should fall right in place....at least mine did - after NOT doing what I described!

I checked my reading - said 1/4 tank in the boat lift, added six gallons, when to 1/2 - 5/8 tank and added another 6 gallons and went to full.

Not sure if 100% accurate - but once I get below 1/4 tank I will know to stay near the dock!

reviewText:
Quality is decent - decent enough to break through a window and slice a seatbelt in an emergency, anyway.  I tried it on an old mirror (bad luck, I know) and some nylon strap I had laying around and it broke the glass and sliced through the nylon just like it was supposed to.  The hammer is small, so I wore a thick leather glove and some glass splinters got on it during the test, though I figure if I had to smash a window to get out of my car, a couple glass splinters would be the least of my worries.  Cars use safety glass anyway, so they'd just crumple into little pieces as opposed to sharp shards.

The only thing about the tool I found sub-par was that the screws holding the two halves together were loose (on both hammers in the 2-pack).  I put some blue Lock-Tite on the screws and re-tightened them firmly on the recessed nuts.  Problem solved, but I was left to wonder if someone took the hammer straight out of the package and put it in the glove compartment, it might come apart when they needed it most.  That cost it a star.

For such a cheap price, it's a little extra safety that might save your life someday, so why not buy one?
summary: These should be mandatory in every car.

The stuff works! When you put the promoter on it drys to a slight haze. Once it is dry you can apply your piece that has the 3M adhesive tape and it is never coming off. This stuff is unforgiving as once you stick your piece into place there is no adjustment, so you have to get it right the first time. This is a great fluid extractor.  I did my first oil change all by myself on my BMW 325CI.  I warmed up the engine for 10-15 minutes.  I just waited till the temp gauge reaches the middle point.  Then I took out the dipstick, inserted the tube down the dipstick pipe till it hit the oil pan.  I only pumped the handle 5-7 times.  You don't want to pump it too much.  It may create too much of a suction and may break a seal or something.  As the container fills up, there is less empty room in the container so it will require less pumping.  Eventually all of your oil will come out.  I sucked up about 6.8 liters of old oil.  It was very easy to do and was actually pretty fun.  While it's sucking the oil out, you can change the oil filter.  Build, seems to be of qood build quality. The only thing I didn't like so much is the tubing.  I wish the connecting gommet was something different.  Maybe a screw like connector would be better.  If your dipstick pipe is big enough, you can try to find a 10mm platic or teflon tube that is about 10 feet long, that would be even better.  That way you don't have to connect the two tubes together.

I have a muscle car that sits relatively low and unlike my previous jack, the XL20 fits under the car perfectly.  At 18.1", it does not raise as high as the 3.5 ton Arcan. It does raise quickly, and with respect to its weight, others reviews state that the XL20 is heavy - well, I guess that's relative statement.... the XL20 is 67 lbs. - which is treat to move around as compared to my previous floor jack -- which is a heavy beast that weighs 107 lbs.  The XL20 is a nice floor jack that I would recommend to others.
summary: Works Great - and it's NOT that heavy!

1.  Well, I followed YouTube and the manufacturer instructions. It was easy to install except the green wire from the left tail light to the right was pretty short. I had to make more adjustments to get enough wire to the right tail light. Unit passed the initial test with a volt meter. 2nd test was to plug in to trailer and go for a test drive. After 5 minutes on the road I stopped to ensure it was operational and the right tail light stopped working. inspected all wires and tested with volt meter and the right tail light of the 4-way flat T-connector failed to function but the left light was working correctly. Used jumpers to test trailer light and all lights including the right tail light are functional. investigated potential wire failures - there were none. I cut the unit out and sent it back to Amazon as a defective item and ordered a 2nd unit. The package said Curt tests every unit before resale, they failed to properly test this one. Both my Dodge and the trailer have LED lights.
2. It's been 1 hr of driving and the 2nd one is still working. There are still 2 issues regarding install, the green wire from the left taillight to the right taillight needs to be longer and the sticky pad for mounting the unit needs to be larger. I used carpet tape to mount mine
08/18/17: the unit failed within 6 months and customer service was no help. they blamed the failure on my vehicle; however, my vehicle is performing just fine when i remove the fuse from the wiring harness. I will not buy another CURT.
summary: this was a defective product both times.

Yeehaw!  Installed these bad boys on my 98 Accord EX (yes, the 4 cylinder) with a little help from some other products on Amazon.  Nice logo, Wisconsin Auto Supply.  These struts are pretty stylin'.

The good news.  These struts are insanely powerful.  They won't pop open on their own (not enough leverage), but they easily hold up the hood and you darn sure aren't compressing them by hand.  Also, my hood, which has always been a pain to fully close, now closes easily.

The bad news.  These struts are insanely powerful.  They bow the hood from the sides in the closed position producing a gap which is very obvious from the sides.  I can't say as that I particularly care.  I can just add some rubber trim and make the hood look cool.  Keep in mind that I'm also using these in a way they weren't intended, so your mileage may vary!

reviewText:
Considering how simple this bug shield is, the installation was remarkably difficult. Part of that is due to how Toyota attaches their grill to the Tundra and this device's need to mount between the grill and the hood. If I had not already been replacing the grill along with installing the bug shield, it would have been even more infuriating.

Besides that, the lousy little screws and "anchors" the manufacturer provides makes for poor attachments on the two sides above the lights. Don't bother with a screwdriver. You can push those into place by hand... and hope they'll stay. Actually screwing them in serves no purpose but to spin a screwdriver.

The bug shield I received is just a bit wavy and warped in the middle. It's not horrible, but would not be a good option for the image-conscious buyer.

The color is just right, unlike the vent shades also made by AVS. Where the vent shades have the color and transparency of cheap, ugly window tint, the bug shield is a nice, dark (yet still slightly translucent) black.

Overall, the product does not leave me wanting to run out and recommend an AVS bug shield to everyone I meet. If anything, I would suggest that another shopper consider other alternatives first. This item isn't the worst possible option, but it's also not satisfying.

My last same-sized container anti-seize lasting me 30 years (home use), so my children will finish this one.

About it:
It's silver in color, 8-oz. container (a bunch), -65F - 1600F, Anti-Seize, -Corrosion and -Galling; has Lid Brush; label indicates "Made in USA".

Specific Use: Ease assembly and disassembly of hardware which experience extreme temperatures and/or corrosive conditions.

I've used this routinely, and sparingly for it does not take much - just a light swipe on threads, mating surfaces etc.  Most of my last container went to lubricating boat and boat engine components for very good saltwater corrosion prevention.

A general caution is: not apply to business end of sparkplug, O2 sensor etc (lightly on threads/sealing surface only) - else could impact component performance (never seen it happen lol).

*UPDATE: I visited Permatex website - wished I'd done so earlier ... A summary:

From Website Technical Data Sheets (TDS),

This Permatex (80078) has ingredients of "aluminum, copper and graphite lubricants ... meets or exceed requirements of Mil Spec Mil-A-907E."
Temperature Range: "-51F to 1600F"
Flash: ">350F"
TDS Applications: "Sparkplug threads, Exhaust & Engine Hardware, Brake Assemblies, Boilers, Ovens, Jet Engines and Turbines.", and does refer to a "Marine" use.

Permatex Copper:  This may be a preferred product due to seemingly inherent do-all capability: Dielectric grease, anti-seize, anti-corrosion to include mating surfaces of dissimilar metals. Specific from TDS, " ... designed for stainless ... contains a high percentage of micro-fine copper flakes in a semi-synthetic, grease carrier and fortified with high quality rust and corrosion inhibitors ... provides good electrical conductivity ... meets Mil Spec A-907."
Temperature Range: "-30F to 1800F"
Flash: "300F"
TDS Applications: "Sparkplug threads installed into aluminum heads, Exhaust & Engine hardware, Oxygen sensors, Knock sensors, Thermostat housing bolts, Fuel filter fittings, Battery cable connections."

Permatex Nickel: Specific from TDS, "Nickel Anti-Seize was designed specifically for use on stainless steel or similar alloys ... use where copper contamination must be avoided, under conditions of extreme pressure and temperature and with stainless steel, titanium and nickel alloys ... contains tenacious metals, oils and graphite materials that cannot be burned away or removed by slow moving parts." Product description also refers "protection of mated dissimilar metals."
Temperature Range:  "-65F to 2400F"
Flash: "200F"
TDS Applications: "Exhaust & Catalytic converter assemblies."

Kyle
summary: Lug Nuts, Spark Plugs, Exhaust & EGR Assy, Marine, List Goes On

reviewText:
Very nice tire pressure gauge. It is pretty much impossible to find a decent one in any store. You basically have the made in china 8 dollar round face gauge that works for a little while until it falls apart or the really stupid pen ones that pop out a ruler that I am not sure why anyone would even bother with those as kicking the tire will tell you about the same information.

The chuck on this swivels so it is very convenient to use at any angle you do not have to twist the hose itself. The gauge is easy to read at night because it glows in the dark. It seems to me like the gauge face is actually glass instead of plastic. The pressure relief button works well. Overall I am very pleased. When comparing this gauge for accuracy to the digital calibrated gauge I use for work it reads right on what it should be. When this gauge read 35 lbs I read 35.2 on my calibrated gauge. Of course you can't see 1/10 resolution with this analog gauge it does however have graduations for every pound.

When it starts to fail dump the innards, re-pack it and your good to go again for pennies on the dollar. From cigg. smokers to herbailist your good to go. Whoever designed this should receive an award. I get no boost spike and the pressure is very finely adjustable. it bolts(well, clamps) in and off I go.

Sure enough it will do 0psi as a good starting point. It's "open" at this point, I can blow through it. After that it's easily dialed up to whatever setting you want.

Be aware it is a manual controller, not electronic so partial throttle can be a bit finnicky, but that's no fault of the product and truth be told I don't have much issue with it. The only thing that really happened is my throttle is more sensitive in the 1/3 pedal travel range but it's still easy to modulate after a learning curve. FWIW I have a manual transmission, results may be different with an automatic.

I have the ATEQ Quickset TPMS for my Subaru and it works perfrectly.  Simple, effective.  I wanted something to poll sensors in order to verify sensor IDs and troubleshoot issues.  I also wanted it to activate dormant sensors.  So, I decided to go with ATEQ's product that matched these requirements, the VT-30.

Well, it didn't go that way.  My first impressions of the device were that it feels like it was made by fisher price.  It's very light for its size, and the buttons are plastc covered, but not in a good way.  They're also not very responsive.  It comes in a silicone case that seems it would do a decent job in a fall, but overall it feels cheap.  For the price, I expected more solidity in the build.

At this point, I was willing to overlook this.  I'm a diy'er, not a professional mechanic.  If it works, it works.  I tried it on my car.  It read the first couple sensors first try with no problems.  After that, it went down hill.  It never read another sensor again.  It would simply say no sensor detected.  I tried various positions, various angles, rain dances, etc which were not required to make it work before.  No dice.

So, I tried updating it.  Installing the software was easy enough.  When it went to update, the device would simply shut off and the software would say it is incompatible.  Per the reviews here, I found you had to hold the enter button, then hit the power button to turn it on in order to put it in a boot loader mode for updates.  Nowhere in the software or any other documentation is that ever mentioned, but there you go.

After updating, it still wouldn't work.  I tried it on the two sensors it managed to read before, nope.  I tried it on my winter set, nope.  I tried it on the wife's car (also a Subaru), nope.  I boxed it back up and sent it back.  I couldn't get it out the door fast enough.

Bottom line:  For the price, it feels cheap and is extremely flakey.  Maybe I got a bad one, but it worked and then it didn't.  The next one could do that a month in instead of 45 seconds.  Not a good track record to appease me.

I ordered an Autel and it worked perfectly and is still working.  It also has a rechargeable Li-Ion battery instead of a 9v.  The only downside is Autel only gives you a year of updates, which doesn't matter to me since it works on our cars now.  Good to go.

Great purchase and would definitely buy again at Amazon's unbeatable price.

reviewText:
Ill first say that I love the innovation and idea behind this product.  The idea is that every modern vehicle has an On-Board Diagnostics II (OBD II) port.  The port is usually located near the drivers left knee, sometimes under a cover or door.  The Automatic device plugs into this, which may, as in our case, require that you completely remove the access door (since once the Automitic Link device is plugged in, the door won't close anymore).  Car servicers and emissions testers connect their diagnostics computer to this port to clear codes and to look at numerous aspects of the engines performance. For most cars, this includes RPM, transmission temperature, coolant temperature, fuel flow, oil pressure, and many other things that show up on your dash display like fuel level.  All of these parameters can be queried by a third-party device, such as Automatics device or a ScanGauge device (which is more customizable and can pull all of this information and can calculate mileage too).  Both the Automatic Link and ScanGuage products are powered by the OBD port.

While ScanGauge pulls a lot of information from the on-board computer and allows you to customize the windows and displayed information, the Automatic Link displays only gas mileage.  Its not clear what other information the device may pull to do its mileage calculation, but it is clear that you cannot customize the interface on your iPhone to see anything else.  This makes sense when you consider that the Automatic device and its required iPhone (or Android) companion app are all built around helping you drive more efficiently.  However, this product is likely to appeal to tech-savvy folks, who will expect access to more information.  So here is a run-down of functionality, pros, and cons:

- Setup was easy.  It automatically detected the vehicle type and VIN.  The con here, of course, its that if you are a privacy-aware, you might expect that this info is being sent to a server somewhere.  You MUST create on online login to use the app.

- The iPhone app links up via Bluetooth.  You can leave the Link device plugged in all the time, so that when you get to your car, it links right back up.

- Battery drain on the iPhone was acceptable.  There is no real-time information displayed while driving, so you can turn your iPhone display off while driving to save battery.

- Each trip, no matter how short or long, is broken into segments, each of which is easy to navigate to on the home screen.  Information saved and displayed for each segment includes miles driven, mpg, fuel cost, time travelled, travel map, and your driving score.  The problem I had was that the mileage calculated was never anywhere close to reality.  I verified this on a long trip where I used the device from fuel stop to fuel stop.  I refilled and calculated refill gallons against odometer miles.  I got 14 mpg by my calcs, and Automatic calculated 7 or 8 mpg each time.  This is a huge difference and presents a major problem for a device that is all about calculating your mileage and helping you with fuel efficiency.  I checked my vehicles compatibility online, and Automatic confirmed that it would detect fill-ups and be able to calculate my mileage within 10%.  Based on what other reviewers are saying, it sounds like this device can be accurate...  Perhaps accuracy varies by vehicle manufacturer and model.

- The unit calculates your driving score (0 to 100), and I was always getting 100.  Im sure Im not that perfect, some fine tuning on this algorithm would be good.  Note that the app does NOT show your driving score or mpg as you drive.

- The Link device makes an audible sound when you go over 70 mpg, brake hard, or accelerate too fast.  This alert behavior was a little erratic when I tested it out.

SUMMARY
Good idea, but with mileage being as far off as it is, some refinement is needed.  Im pretty sure I won't save $100 gas by just using this device, so I think the developers need to broaden the appeal by allowing users to access more information.  Perhaps they could allow users to set up other screens (access with a swipe) to see other information such as tranny temp, coolant temp, rpms, and other tings that the on-board computer provides.  This is a fun gadget with a lot of potential; just needs some refinement and better mpg calculation.
summary: Nice start; needs some improvements to be truly useful; mpg was way off, which is a problem

reviewText: So far I used it on my own car, to see what the check engine light came on for and was able to clear it with no problems. I had topped off  my gas tank using a gas can and had filled it up too full and the check engine light came on, when this scanner came and I hooked it up it told me that the problem was with the fuel tank and I knew immediately that it was because I over filled it. You also hear about people that do not close their gas cap completely, and that alone might throw a check engine light. I cleared the check engine light and it never came back on for that problem again. I also used it three times on friends cars . Very useful equipment for today's computer controlled cars . Easy to use just follow the instructions on the screen. Already paid for itself. 11-14-14 Update My car was  missing badly and the check engine light came on, this happen twice and I hooked up this scanner and it told me exactly what the problem was a bad ignition coil. I replace the coil with a set that I found on E Bay which was new and cheap and my cars runs great again. Just think what a mechanic would charge you for repairing this type of problem, this thing paid for itself on the second time i used it. I also did a similar problem on my friends Lexus RX 330, can you imagine if he took it to a Toyota dealer to get it fixed and how much it would have cost him, we live in Hawaii so double what you would pay in the mainland ... he paid $50.00 for a new coil. I am not a mechanic, but have some skills and this is so easy to use. Highly recommended

This stuff actually works, but doesn't work like a lot of people think. It isn't some miracle 'fix it in 3 seconds' additive...it is a full restorative additive that once added, you really need to top off the battery with distilled water and give the battery a good deep charge. In a day or so, even old batteries come back to life.

It kills the calcium build up that weakens the plate charges in older 'set' batteries.  It isn't meant to actually 'add voltage', though on a dead battery it will, of course...it is meant to restore cankered plates inside the battery to 'like new'.  Great to start out a new battery on this stuff...I've added it to mine since the mid-80's.  You don't notice a difference until the battery is several years old...when it should be dying, and it isn't.  I've got a 9-year old battery in my truck that is still as strong as the day it was bought. Twice, last year, I left my lights on for hours, killed the battery...and yet, with a quick jump from a good Samaritan, was up and running in minutes. My alternator had it back to full charge both times, in less than 4-hours.  This bottle is like 'buying two batteries for the price of 1'...just make sure you have open 'wet-cell caps' on your battery to add it...and follow the directions first.

BTW...most know this, but it doesn't fix busted charging systems...so if your alternator isn't charging in the 13.5-15v range, forget it...this is not 'liquid alternator'.
summary: Great stuff, but hard to find locally now

reviewText: I bought one directly from AFE and it does work. I wanted to make sure i review an actual product sold to me by AFE directly before I take to Amazon Prime. As the vehicle owner thats something you may want to look up prior to going aftermarket because a dealer can void warranty claim if the filter is linked in the  slightest way to any failure. I have many friends that work for Dealers as mechanics and we all know the last thing they want is to do work if your claim is under a extended warranty contract. Unless it's manufactured claim then thats different because they get paid either way. I came across another brand and that does state that if the filter caused any damage that they would pay for damages that may come from the use of the filter wich in this case it will ve between dealer and filter company. They guarantee you the quality and compatibility to your engine so why not I said. The brand is EcoGard  and part number is X10232. Now im only posting my review from my own personal experience and I am in no way liable to any problem you may run into from using anything on your car. As a side note, while you have the blower completely disassembled to replace this part, clean out the AC evaporator. Mine was clogged and filthy and the AC actually works much much better now.
summary: Fixed 2002 Ford Explorer Sport Trac AC settings 1-3

reviewText:
I've been using Wheel Wax on various sets of wheels on my cars for about three years now on both painted and clearcoated polished aluminum. Before that, I used to use conventional car polish. This product is superior for several reasons. First it definitely lasts longer; I generally only apply it once a year though I suppose twice a year or more might be needed for a car driven more miles. Even toward the end of the year, I find that water still beads on the wheel pretty well, unlike it would on an untreated wheel. Supposedly this product is more heat resistant than a conventional car wax, thus lasting longer on the hot surface of a wheel.

I agree with other comments that this product does not actually repel brake dust in the sense that you'll still see a dusting of it accumulating on the wheel as you drive. However it makes it much easier to wash the brake residue off the wheel assuming you do this somewhat regularly. I wouldn't expect any product to eliminate the need for washing your wheels.

As an added bonus Wheel Wax has a rich texture and applies smoothly, then is easy to remove with minimal buffing. Also it has a nice scent.
summary: May not repel brake dust, but makes wheel cleaning easier

reviewText: OEM style fender rivets for 2006 Grand Cherokee. They work.

Ordered 4 gauge x 12ft "OxGord" cables, received Pennzoil brand instead. Honestly couldn't care less what brand is on them, so long as they're as described. Unfortunately, they're absolutely not as described.

The clamps have stout springs and a nice finish to them, better fit than I've seen in a lot of other cables, honestly. The jaws close square and don't have a ton of slop in them. The cable itself is only tied to one side of the clamp, leaving a relatively small rivet and minimal surface contact between the clamp "halves" to carry the balance of current. Even then closing spring is isolated from the two halves and not resting on the handle itself, a trick often used in cheaper clamps in place of a dedicated conductor.

Worse still; the cables are *not* 4AWG. In fact, they're nothing. They're marked in no way, anywhere along their length. I've never had a job that would allow using unmarked mystery cable, and I'm not really inclined to do so myself. Out of curiosity, I cut the cables open, and just like another reviewer, I found them to be notably undersized for "4 gauge." They measure out to just between 5 and 6 gauge, which would explain why they're unmarked.

You get what you pay for, and these "Made in China" cables are no exception.

I bought these knowing full-well I would never use them to attempt to start a vehicle, and bought "oversized" cables to be safe for my application. Seeing what they are, they're being relegated to the junk shelf for potential future projects with lower demand. I personally wouldn't trust these to start anything larger than a 1.8L gas engine in warm weather, assuming the battery is in good shape and clean terminals, and I'd consider that a gamble.

If you're just looking for peace of mind by having a cheap set of cables in the back of your car, go ahead and buy these. Just please, PLEASE make sure you've got a fire extinguisher to go with them, and use the other guy's cables first.
summary: Don't buy these if you plan to use them.

I replaced the completely flat/slightly frowning leafs on my 98 XJ and got about 1" - 1.25" lift - they say these are heavy duty, but actually they are pretty close to the stock leafs.  There are other parts out there for bigger lift - so if you want 2-3" look elsewhere.

My XJ is pretty little rust, so i had no issues getting mine out - WORK THE BOLTS SLOWLY - SLOWLY.  Half turn out, quarter turn in - repeat. for the front bolt,  I used an 18" breaker bar with a 4' iron tube as an extension - used a 12" ratchet extension so that I could stand next to the jeep and work the bolt.  A pickle fork works well to pull the bolt out once it's free of the nut.

In the back bolt - use a 13/16 wrench (do NOT attempt to use vice grips - you WILL round the nut) on the opposite side.  For me, on the passenger side, the hitch was in the way of pulling the bolt out - so I got it out far enough to cut it off with a angle grinder and then pulled it out by the nut on the other side.  Found a grade 8 bolt at lowes that worked just fine as a replacement.  When I got the driver side, it was reverse and i didn't have to cut anything.

I locked the truck and before I could get around it, they came back on again by themselves. A bad solid state relay was the culprit. I removed it, looked it up to find the replacement, and noticed it was not OEM, but one from a local box store. The one right next to it in the fuse block was an original AC Delco part, and was still working fine, so I made sure I ordered an original to replace it. Been working fine ever since. When it comes to auto parts, I stick with what I can trust, and that's usually AC Delco.
summary: Stick with AC Delco for trustworthy and reliable parts

reviewText:
I think this is more  for people who enjoy going to car shows and standing out a bit. It isn't very practical, and in my state  it is illegal, to use the colored lights while driving. Even the white light doesn't seem bright enough for me. I live in the hills and I like to have plenty of bright light when I'm driving so I can see and avoid critters from a distance before it's too late. The lights are fun and I think I would really love the interior lights, but I have already taken these off my "every day" car in favor of my brighter headlights. Using the audio mode was cool. I think young people would love these, but I would recommend using it only in car shows for legal and safety reasons.

One problem I have with these is that they work and are controlled with an app on your phone. What happens if you're driving and the app fails? Do the lights go out? If that happens it could be a very dangerous situation. I think we are trusting technology such as this far too much to be safe. This app, like all other apps, has too much possibility of either crashing or being hacked. So I would never use this as my main headlights. It's easy enough to install and uninstall to use it for fun at the right times, though.

Note: It has come to my understanding that it may not be possible for the app to turn the headlights completely off.
summary: Easy to install. Fun novelty, especially for car enthusiasts.

reviewText:
These earbuds offer good noise isolation and very good sound quality.  I use my Uclear HBC220 headsets on a motorcycle, with a Garmin Zumo 590LM and iPhone for GPS directions, a variety of music inputs and phone communications.  These fit easily in my Shoei helmet that also has the speakers installed, so I can choose to use speakers or earbuds depending on what is plugged into the Uclear tranceiver.

The earbuds incorporate a microphone in the wires that hang down from the earbuds. I am able to not only hear good music with significantly reduced background noise, but bike-to bike communications and phone calls are clear, without noticeable wind or vehicle noise intruding on conversations.  Most calls are clear, but if the microphones are not properly places, people I talk to will complain of some echo.  I don't know how the mic picks up clear, noise free voice, but it does.  I appreciate not having the boom microphone in front of my mouth where it often interferes in a helmet.

Trouble free, comfortable and good sound quality, and these replace the hearing protection earplugs I otherwise wear on the bike.
summary: Hearing protection, Great sound and voice transmission in one package

reviewText: Just like OEM perfect match, saved a ton of money.
It's a near-perfect color match. From a distance, you can't tell the original color from the Dupli-Color paint.

I've run my engine after the work I did with this for a couple thousand miles now.  I have no leaks where this was used.

It is quite forgiving to work with at 80F+ temperatures - although it can be a little soft at this temperature.  For example, I used this to seal some half-moon inserts before attaching a valve cover.  The half moons did not immediately set in place, so I had to be careful about how they shifted during installation of the valve cover.  I couldn't let them soft-set before installation because the half-moons wanted to turn to be flat-topped to gravity.  If it was cooler, I'm certain this would not have been an issue.

Regardless, I'm very happy with the seal that this formed.  Vehicles and applications vary on which color RTV is best.  I highly recommend this for work on Toyota 4Runners.
