reviewText:
Used this to remove a vinyl sticker off the back glass of my gf's car.  Sticker was about 4" by 6" in size and I used maybe 5% of the total pad to removed it.  I did this over a few days instead of all at once just to make sure everything was going well and that I didn't damage the glass.  Eventually I got use to it and tried with a 20V Dewalt to press harder than you would ever press normally just to test it out, and no damage was done.

Like I said, I used it a few days and let the weather work on the sticker and glue over time.  The sticker was applied years before.  As you use the eraser pad, it comes off like the eraser of an old wooden pencil and will make a mess if you're using it in the garage.  Nothing big, but you will need to sweep it up if you like to keep a clean garage.

I was very pleased with the product and feel like it will keep being useful over the years.  I haven't tried it on a painted surface yet, but from reviews I've read it appears to be safe.
summary: Good eraser, did the job without hassle

I purchased this for a 2005 Ford Expedition that I was towing a 5,500 pound RV trailer.  The towing that I do with the Expedition is fairly close to home (usually within 125 miles radius of home) and usually relatively flat. On occasion I do it some significant hills when taking the RV out to western MA. These combined had me concerned with loads and temps on the tranny.

I puchased (from Anmazon) a engine codes monitor that bluetooth's onto a smartphone or tablet, and started monitoring the tranny temp (via that set up). This was much easier than installing a trans temp gauge. The somewhat flat ride pulling the trailer down the interstate, on an 83 degree day had the tranny temp at 193 - 197 range.

This week I repeated the same exact trip (same camp ground) with an 85 degree day. The tranny temps climbed and stopped at a max of 161 degrees, with a range of 157 - 161. This offers great piece of mind running the tranny temps 30+ degrees cooler.

As noted, at 1st I was skeptical, as when I first installed the cooler, I noticed no diff in non-trailer towing temps (which generally ran between 147 and 155 depending on rpm and duration at that rpm).  So when not pulling the trailer, I was seeing no diff in temps before or after the cooler install. So I concluded it was not going to make much of a diff.  But in pulling the trailer, there is a large diff in temps. What I think is happening here is that the Tru-Cool unit has a calibrated flow section that only allows full flow of fluid once the tranny fluid thins out at higher temps. Without pulling the trailer, the fluid never really gets hot enough (the stock cooler or this supplemental cooler) and thins out enough to flow through all the vanes of the Tru Cool cooler (as that cooling capacity is not needed at those temps). But as the fluid got hotter and thinner, it does flow through those vanes that have a calibrated flow rate to them. Once the fluid is flowing through those vanes, at least for me,  the temps stopped increasing due to the extra cooling capacity. This is the design of this unit, and you know what... it really works.

Installation Notes:
*  The cooler is a universal fit (as most coolers are) so you may need to get creative where and how you mount it and plumb the hoses.. Expect (as I imagine you already do) to be a little creative making some kind of mounting brackets and hose connectors. Ditto the mounting instructions are equally generic. You are assumed to have some basic mechanical ability
*  The instructions are a bit misleading in that i says can be mounted in any orientation. That is true, it will work in any orientation, but it will be vastly more effective with the input / output barbs facing in the up orientation (this allows air to purge form the system, otherwise the top section of the cooler can become air-locked and effectively reduce / eliminate that cooling surface / capacity).  I spoke with Dana (makers of Tru-Cool) during the installation and they both confirmed this point and highly recommend the barbs up mounting. They acknowledged that their installation literature should be stating this 'much preferred' install orientation rather than be stating simply that 'it can be installed in any orientation'.

Anyway... I have been using it for 3 weeks now. I highly recommend it. I will provide a long term update once I have some real miles under it.

Hope this review helps in your purch decision. if yes, give it a thumbs up vote.

Cheers - Jim
summary: Usage in Ford Expedition - At first skeptical after the install, but has proved excellent at reducing tranny fluid temp

I've been a satisfied buyer and user of K&N Products for decades, and for several reasons:

1.- ALL K&N Products are proudly made in the U.S.A., keeping American jobs right here !!
2.- Builders, racers, and average motorists alike know that K&N's Oiled Gauze filtering media traps and holds the finest dirt particles while allowing a full flow of clean air to the engine.
3.- The industry's only MILLION-MILE WARRANTY.
4.- The initial cost SEEMS high, but being able to use the same filter again and again for several years makes the K&N a bargain.
5.- A white-glove inspection of the inside of the throttle body after 50,000 miles shows NO DIRT has gotten past the Oiled Gauze filtering medium.
6.- Unlike OEM-type paper filters, the K&N filter WORKS WHEN WET, so your vehicle is 100% driveable in heavy rain.
 A careful cleaning and re-oiling every 50,000 miles with the K&N "FilterCharger" Kit (available at Amazon) will keep your K&N's like-new  performance for years. Be careful not to OVER-OIL the pleats !!

 There are 2 types of Filtercharger Kits -- a "Squeeze Bottle" and an "Aerosol Can". After using both types, I find that it's MUCH easier to do a perfect job AND keep things neat if I avoid the Aerosol Can and go with the easier-to-control Squeeze Bottle. It's IMPORTANT that we don't apply TOO MUCH of the sticky "oil" to the filter pleats.

 NOTE:  Modern Fuel-Injected engines have "MAF Sensors" that are VERY sensitive to air-borne contaminants, and if too much oil is applied at filter-servicing, the results will be a contaminated MAF sensor -- and the resulting lack of performance and fuel economy.
 When servicing the K&N, you can avoid the contamination problem by removing the MAF sensor and cleaning it thoroughly with "CRC Mass Air Flow Sensor Cleaner" -- available at Amazon -- Follow the directions on the can EXACTLY, and your engine will run smoother and you'll save gas, too !!

If you are not prepared to properly care for your K&N Air Filter, DON'T buy one !!! Use the factory equipment Motorcraft and change every 12,000 miles.
 Good Luck !!

My wife and I both agree that these blades suck.  I'm really not happy about it. And would love to hear if Valeo is prepared to swap my Ultimates for Gen 2s.
________________________________________
OCTOBER 27 2013 UPDATE
______________________________________________________

I thought it only fair to post an update to this review. After writing the original review, I also wrote to Valeo Customer Service and overnight I got a reply from a Valeo Rep offering a refund or a product swap.  I opted for a new set of Gen 2 blades and within a couple of days a set arrived for each vehicle and they are both of calibre and performance I have come to expect.  I can say I am a Valeo (Gen2) customer for life.
summary: Not Up To Normal Valeo Quality

reviewText:
The two-piece product has good initial quality seems well made.  I actually like the neck/head pillow more as it is very adjustable and stays in place.  However, the back cushion doesn't work well for me.  Everybody has different body styles and car seats so each person may experience different results.  Here are the pluses and minuses that I experienced in my first week of ownership:

PLUSES:
- well made product (initial quality)
- beautiful design (looks nice and won't interfere with the seat's side airbags)
- adjustable back cushion in the sense that you can raise it up to find the right height
- nice neck/head cushion
- doesn't slide out of the car when you exit

MINUSES:
- the back cushion is very cylindrical (curved) with substantial support on the sides, providing lots of support on the sides of one's back (one can feel it pushing in); but for me, it was far too much
- your car seat will need to be pushed back a lot more to accompany the depth of the cushion as a result of that substantial side support; that takes away from a lot of the rear-seat room
- the lumbar support, regrettably, is minimal; and that lumbar area ironically seem to compress significantly with the memory foarm
(note: my advice to the manufacturer was to use a stiffer formula for the lumbar section, or put a lot more lumbar foam in that region)

I'm not so forgetful that I need a full blown checklist when I change my oil. I've never forgotten to replace the drain plug, or put in oil, etc. However, black tire chocks can sometimes do a good job of... uh... hiding themselves.

Seeing the bright orange chocks serves as a reminder that you're not totally done yet.

As far as durability goes, I have to agree with other reviewers here. If you're like me, and go all out to ensure you're doing things "the right way", they're fine. Would I trust them behind a small to medium sized car with a working parking brake? Sure. Would I trust them to keep a full size pickup with a bad emergency brake on ramps? Never.
summary: There's one reason to own these...
